gister: Penarth |date= |accessdate= 4 April 2020|work= Imperial War Museum}}</ref><ref>{{cadw |num= 13340 |desc= Cenotaph|accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Wrexham war memorial (8).JPG\n| commonscat = Wrexham war memorial\n| subject = [[Royal Welch Fusiliers]] memorial\n| location = Junction of Bodhfryd Rd. & Chester Rd., [[Wrexham]] \n| date = 1924\n| type = Twin sculptures on pedestal\n| material = Bronze and stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = <ref>{{cite web |author=|url=https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/17816 |title=War Memorials Register: Royal Welch Fusiliers |date= |accessdate= 3 April 2020|work= Imperial War Museum}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = CarmarthenCountyWarMemorial.jpg\n| commonscat = \n| subject = Carmarthen County war memorial  \n| location = Priory Street,  [[Carmarthen]]\n| date = 1924\n| type = Statue on pedestal and plinth\n| material = Bronze and Portland stone\n| dimensions = 4.5m high\n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = <ref>{{cite web |author=|url= https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/6809 |title=War Memorials Register, Carmarthenshire |date= |accessdate=4 April 2020|work=Imperial War Museum}}</ref> \n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Llandaff War Memorial.JPG\n| commonscat = Llandaff War Memorial\n| subject = Llandaff Cathedral School war memorial\n| location = Cathedral Green, [[Llandaff]], Cardiff \n| date = 1924\n| type = 3 Sculptures on pedestals\n| material = Bronze and stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation = Grade II\n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = Q29491677\n| notes = <ref>{{cite web |author=|url=https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/6688 |title=War Memorials Register: Llandaff and Llandaff Cathedral School |date= |accessdate= 4 April 2020|work= Imperial War Museum}}</ref><ref>{{cadw |num= 13703 |desc= Llandaff War Memorial|accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Statue of James Rice Buckley, Llandaff 2011 2.jpg\n| commonscat = Statue of James Rice Buckley, Llandaff\n| subject = [[James Buckley (priest)|James Rice Buckley]]\n| location = Cathedral Green, [[Llandaff]]\n| date = 1927\n| type = Statue on pedestal\n| material = Bronze & granite\n| dimensions =\n| designation = Grade II\n| coordinates = \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = Q29491672\n| notes = <ref>{{cadw |num= 13698 |desc= Statue of James Rice Buckley |accessdate= 5 March 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = \n| commonscat = \n| subject = Basil Webb\n| location = Crypt of Lady Chapel, [[Hereford Cathedral]] \n| date = \n| type = [[reredos|Reredos]] with figures of 3 saints \n| material = \n| dimensions = \n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= \n| wikidata = \n| notes = Basil Webb was the son of [[Sir Henry Webb, 1st Baronet|Henry Webb]] who funded the memorial.<ref>{{cite web |author=|url=https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/32514 |title=War Memorials Register: Basil Webb |date= |accessdate= 5 April 2020|work= Imperial War Museum}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n===Other artworks===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px;\"| Name\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px;\"| Location\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:600px;\"| Comments\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"| Image\n|-\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|-\n|''The Boy Scout''\n|\n|Goscombe John executed this bronze in 1910 and it is currently held in the collection of the Amgueddfa Cymru Caerdydd [National Museum of Wales, Cardiff] Accession number: NMW A 126. It was the gift of Lady Webb. This figure was first exhibited at the Royal Academy in 1910 and is in fact a portrait of Basil Webb, the only son of [[Sir Henry Webb, 1st Baronet|Henry Webb]], of Llwynarthau, Monmouthshire, a Liberal MP and mining engineer, who was a director of David Davies's Ocean Coal Company. The sitter served as a 2nd lieutenant with the Welsh Guards during the First World War and was killed in December 1917. See entry above. This sculpture was included in \"An Exhibition of Works by Certain Modern Artists of Welsh Birth or Extraction\" held in 1913\u201314<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/43.html ''The Boy Scout''] Victorian Web. Retrieved 19 November 2012</ref>\n|[[File:Basil Webb 2.jpg|150px]]\n|-\n|''Merlin and Arthur''\n|[[Cardiff]]\n|Another work held in the collection of the Amgueddfa Cymru Caerdydd [National Museum of Wales, Cardiff] Accession number: NMW A 127. This work dates to circa 1896. This bronze was exhibited at The Royal Academy in 1902.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/39.html ''Merlin and Arthur''] Victorian Web. Retrieved 19 November 2012</ref>\n|\n|-\n|Tomb of Dean Vaughan\n|[[Llandaff]]\n|In 1900 Goscombe John executed a marble, life-sized depiction for Vaughan's tomb in Llandaff Cathedral (north choir-aisle)<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/37.html Tomb of Dean Vaughan] Victorian Web. Retrieved 19 November 2012</ref>\n|[[File:Tomb of Dean Vaughan.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|Memorial Relief to the late Canon Guy D.D\n|[[Llandaff]]\n|Also in Llandaff Cathedral, Goscombe John executed this relief in 1897 according to Academy Architecture and Architectural Review, No. 1996.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/33.html Memorial Relief to the late Canon Guy D.D] Victorian Web. Retrieved 19 November 2012</ref>\n|\n|-\n|Statue of John Viriamu Jones\n|Cardiff\n|The Statue of [[John Viriamu Jones]] stands in the entrance hall of the Main Building of [[Cardiff University]], in [[Cathays Park]].\n|[[File:Statue of John Viriamu Jones.jpg|150px]]\n|-\n|The Elf\n|[[Glasgow]]\n|A statue on display in the Kibble Palace, Botanic Gardens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/17c.html|title=\u201cThe Elf\u201d by Sir William Goscombe John|website=www.victorianweb.org|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n|[[File:The Elf, by Sir William Goscombe John.jpg|150px]]\n|}\n\nJohn's output also included:\n[[File:EB1911 Plate IV. v24, pg.505, Fig 10.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Saint John the Baptist]]\n*Statue of [[Saint John the Baptist]].<ref>[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], ed. 1911, vol. 24, pg. 505, Plate IV.</ref>\n*Sculptures on Electra House in Moorgate, City of London, these dating from 1900 to 1903 and representing Egypt, Japan, India and China.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/32.html Sculptures on Electra House] Victorian Web. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref>\n*Equestrian Statue of Edward VII on Pier Head, Liverpool.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/10b.html Equestrian Statue of Edward VII] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006221312/http://victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/10b.html |date=6 October 2012 }} Victorian Web. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref><ref name=\"BuckmanVol1\"/>\n*Statue of Judge Gwilym Williams in Cathays Park, Cardiff.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/18.html Judge Gwilym Williams] Victorian Web. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref>\n*The work ''Grief'' dating to 1890.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/5.html ''Grief''] Victorian Web. Retrieved 19 November 2012</ref>\n*Queen Alexandra. Statue on the facade of the Victoria & Albert Museum.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/22.html Queen Alexandra] Victorian Web. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref>\n*Carved figures on a reredos in St John the Baptist Church, St John Street, Cardiff.<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/john/20.html Reredos in St John the Baptist Church] Victorian Web. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref>\n*Evan James and James James Statues in Pontypridd, Rhondda Cynon Taf. Evan James, bardic name Ieuan ap Iago was a weaver and poet and James James, bardic name Iago ap Ieuan was a harpist and musician. They wrote the tune and the lyrics of Hen Wlad fy Nhadau (\"Land of my Fathers\"), the national anthem of Wales. This Goscombe John work dates to 1930 and is located in Ynysangharad Park.<ref>[http://www.vanderkrogt.net/statues/object.php?record=gbwa037&webpage=ST Evan James and James James Statues] Hither & Dither. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref>\n*Statue of [[Daniel Owen]] in [[Mold, Flintshire]].<ref>[http://www.vanderkrogt.net/statues/object.php?webpage=ST&record=gbwa149 Daniel Owen] Hither & Dither. Retrieved 20 November 2012</ref>\n* Designed the regalia for the investiture of the [[George V|Prince of Wales]] at Carnarvon in 1911.<ref name=\"BuckmanVol1\"/>\n* Designd the [[King George V Silver Jubilee Medal]] in 1935.<ref name=\"BuckmanVol1\"/>\n\nGoscombe John's output was prolific and also includes the seated statue of the [[Duke of Devonshire]], at [[Eastbourne]], [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|King Edward VII]], at [[Cape Town]]; [[Prince Christian Victor of Schleswig-Holstein|Prince Christian Victor]], at [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]]; the historian [[William Edward Hartpole Lecky|Lecky]] at [[Trinity College, Dublin]], and the equestrian statue of the [[Earl of Minto]] at [[Kolkata|Calcutta]]. Goscombe John also executed the monument to the Marquis of Salisbury, in [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref name=\"BuckmanVol1\"/> and Hatfield Church.\n\nThe National Museum of Wales holds many works by Goscombe John.<ref>[http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/art/online/?action=show_works&item=409&type=artist Some works held by the National Museum of Wales] National Museum of Wales. Retrieved 19 November 2012</ref><ref name=\"BuckmanVol1\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n*{{NIE}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Goscombe_John John, Sir William Goscombe (1860\u20131952) Article on Goscombe John's work with images] from The National Archives.\n* [http://www.racollection.org.uk/ixbin/indexplus?_IXACTION_=file&_IXFILE_=templates/full/person.html&_IXTRAIL_=Academicians&person=5746 Profile on Royal Academy of Arts Collections]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John, Goscombe}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh sculptors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Leopold II]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hampstead Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff School of Art and Design]]\n[[Category:20th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the City and Guilds of London Art School]] \n[[Category:20th-century Welsh artists]] \n[[Category:19th-century Welsh artists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Athenaeum Club, London]]\n", "name_user": "Steve Parlanti", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goscombe_John"}
{"title_page": "Naoko Matsumoto", "text_new": "'''Naoko Matsumoto''' is a Professor in the Department of Archaeology at [[Okayama University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://okayama.pure.elsevier.com/en/persons/naoko-matsumoto|title=Naoko Matsumoto|website=Okayama University|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayama-u.ac.jp/user/arch/en/about/index.html|title=About US:Department of Archaeology, Okayama University|website=www.okayama-u.ac.jp|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> Her research covers the areas of cognitive archaeology, gender archaeology and the [[J\u014dmon period|Jomon]] period.\n\n== Education ==\nIn 1998 she received a received her D.Litt.  from [[Kyushu University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bearchaeo.com/matsumoto-biography|title=Matsumoto Biography {{!}} BeArchaeo Project - BEyond ARCHAEOlogy|website=Bearchaeo|language=it|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMatsumoto has excavated at several [[J\u014dmon period|Jomon]] and [[Yayoi period|Yayoi]] sites in the Kyushu and Chugoku districts of western Japan.<ref name=\":0\" /> She is on the Advisory Committee for the Shanghai Archaeology Forum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shanghaiarchaeologyforum.wordpress.com/people/advisory-committee/|title=Advisory Committee \u54a8\u8be2\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a|date=2013-04-18|website=SHANGHAI ARCHAEOLOGY FORUM|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\nMatsumoto, N. 2018. Changing relationship between the dead and the living in Japanese prehistory. ''[[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B]]'': Biological Sciences. 373, 1754, 20170272\n\nMatsumoto, N. 2018. Japan: The Earliest Evidence of Complex Technology for Creating Durable Coloured Goods. ''Open Archaeology''. 4, 1, p.&nbsp;206-216.\n\nMatsumoto, N., Bessho, H. and Tomii, M. (eds) 2011. ''Coexistence and Cultural Transmission in East Asia.'' Left Coast Press.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese archaeologists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Naoko Matsumoto''' is a Professor in the Department of Archaeology at [[Okayama University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://okayama.pure.elsevier.com/en/persons/naoko-matsumoto|title=Naoko Matsumoto|website=Okayama University|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayama-u.ac.jp/user/arch/en/about/index.html|title=About US:Department of Archaeology, Okayama University|website=www.okayama-u.ac.jp|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> Her research covers the areas of cognitive archaeology, gender archaeology and the [[J\u014dmon period|Jomon]] period.\n\n== Education ==\nIn 1998 she received a received her D.Litt.  from [[Kyushu University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bearchaeo.com/matsumoto-biography|title=Matsumoto Biography {{!}} BeArchaeo Project - BEyond ARCHAEOlogy|website=Bearchaeo|language=it|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMatsumoto has excavated at several [[J\u014dmon period|Jomon]] and [[Yayoi period|Yayoi]] sites in the Kyushu and Chugoku districts of western Japan.<ref name=\":0\" /> She is on the Advisory Committee for the Shanghai Archaeology Forum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shanghaiarchaeologyforum.wordpress.com/people/advisory-committee/|title=Advisory Committee \u54a8\u8be2\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a|date=2013-04-18|website=SHANGHAI ARCHAEOLOGY FORUM|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\nMatsumoto, N. 2018. Changing relationship between the dead and the living in Japanese prehistory. ''[[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B]]'': Biological Sciences. 373, 1754, 20170272\n\nMatsumoto, N. 2018. Japan: The Earliest Evidence of Complex Technology for Creating Durable Coloured Goods. ''Open Archaeology''. 4, 1, p. 206-216.\n\nMatsumoto, N., Bessho, H. and Tomii, M. (eds) 2011. ''Coexistence and Cultural Transmission in East Asia.'' Left Coast Press.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese archaeologists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naoko_Matsumoto"}
{"title_page": "Battle of the Bagradas River (c. 240 BC)", "text_new": "{{short description|Battle during the First Punic War}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict    = Battle of the Bagradas River\n|partof      = Carthage's [[Mercenary War]]\n| image      = Macar240.PNG\n| image_size = 300\n|caption     =\n|date        = Autumn 240 BC\n|place       = [[Medjerda River]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type    =\n|map_relief  =\n|latitude    =\n|longitude   =\n|map_size    =\n|map_marksize =\n|map_caption =\n|map_label   =\n|territory   =\n|result      = Carthaginian victory\n|status      =\n|combatants_header =\n|combatant1  = [[Ancient Carthage|Carthage]]\n|combatant2  = Rebel mercenaries<br>Rebelling Libyan towns and cities\n|commander1  = [[Hamilcar Barca]]<ref>Polybius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#73 1:73.1].</ref>\n|commander2  = Spendius\n|units1      =\n|units2      =\n|strength1   = <br>8,000 infantry, 2,000 cavalry, 70 elephants<ref>Polybius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#75 1:75.1-75.2].</ref>\n|strength2   = Unclear, an estimated 25,000. 15,000 under Spendius at [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]], 10,000 near the bridge on Bagradas River.<ref>Polybius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#73 1:76.1]</ref>\n|casualties1 = Unknown\n|casualties2 = 6,000 killed<br>2,000 captured\n|casualties3 =\n|notes       =\n|campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Mercenary War}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of the Bagradas River''' or '''the Macar''' ({{c.|240}}{{nbsp}}BC) was fought between [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] forces and part of the combined forces of Carthage's former [[mercenary]] armies during the [[Mercenary War]] which it used to conduct the [[First Punic War]] and those of rebelling Libyan cities. After the forces of [[Hanno the Great]] were defeated at [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]], and failed to engage the mercenaries afterwards despite favorable conditions, Carthage raised a new army under [[Hamilcar Barca]] in Carthage. Hamilcar managed to leave Carthage despite the rebel blockade of the city and cross the Bagradas River (the ancient name of the [[Medjerda River|Medjerda]]). Rebel armies from besieging Utica and the camp guarded the bridge on the Bagradas River. Hamilcar Barca, by brilliant maneuvering, defeated the combined rebel army. This was the first major Carthaginian victory of the war. A description of the battle forms one of the grandiose set-piece scenes of [[Gustave Flaubert]]'s novel, Salammbo.\n\n== Background ==\n{{further|Mercenary War}}\nThe [[First Punic War]] ended with the Roman victory in the [[Battle of Aegates Islands|Battle of the Aegates Islands]] in March 241 BC and Carthage authorizing [[Hamilcar Barca]] to start peace negotiations with Rome. The eventual settlement between [[Roman republic|Rome]] and Carthage included evacuation of Sicily by Carthage and payment of 3,200 silver talents to Rome as war reparations: 1,000 (21 tons of silver) immediately and 2,200 (56 ton of silver) in ten yearly installments. After paying Rome the indemnity which was part of the treaty,<ref>Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#62 1:62.8-63.3].</ref> it could not easily pay the army of some 20,000 [[mercenaries]] it had employed to fight against Rome.<ref name=\"PAY\">Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#66 66.5], and [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#68 1:68.12]</ref>\n\nDelays in dealing with the mercenaries eventually led to the gathering of the entire army and their families in Sicca Veneria (modern [[El Kef]]), where they demanded payment from the Carthaginian negotiator [[Hanno the Great]].<ref>Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#66 1:66.6-66.12].</ref> The exact amount owned the mercenaries can only be guessed, but given the back pay, ration money and any other rewards promised, it probably was a substantial amount,<ref name=\"Hoyos Dexter pp27-31\">Hoyos Dexter, The Truceless War, p. 27\u201331</ref> which the mercenaries inflated after they reached Sicca. When Hanno refused their demands, as Carthage actually hoped to reduce the payment amount, and mercenaries were unsympathetic about the financial difficulties of Carthage, the negotiations broke down and the mercenaries seized [[Tunis]].<ref>Po0lybius 1.66.1-1.6712</ref> Carthage then sent provisions to Tunis and agreed to all the demands of the mercenaries, and sent Gisco to pay off the demanded amount.<ref>Appian, [https://www.livius.org/ap-ark/appian/appian_sicily.html#%A74 2.7]; Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#67 1:67.1-68.13].</ref>\n\nGisco began to pay off the mercenaries nationality by nationality,<ref>Polybius 1.68.1, 1.69.3</ref> and events might have ended there, but two mercenary leaders, Spendius and Mathos, fomented revolt among the Libyan troops, for their own personal reasons, and were eventually able to persuade the entire mercenary army to revolt. The mercenaries seized the Carthaginian negotiators and the money. Matho used the funds to pay off the amount due to the mercenaries and fund the war effort.<ref>Polybius 1.69.4, 1.70.6</ref> After settling the mercenary payments, the rebels called upon the Libyan towns and cities under Carthaginian control to join the revolt. Several Libyan cities joined the revolt, providing men and funds (Libyan women donated personal possessions and jewels)<ref>Polybius 1.72.5-6</ref> to gather a force of 70,000.<ref>Polybius 1.70.8-9</ref> These events probably took place in the autumn-winter of 241 BC.\n\n==Opening moves==\nMatho divided the rebel army into several detachments. Matho took two armies to cut off the cities of [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]] and Hippacritae, while an army took up position along the only bridge over the River Macar linking Carthage and Utica. Spendius cut off Carthage from the mainland<ref>Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#68 1:68.4-68.13].</ref> while rebels made Tunis their main base. The rebels had no siege weapons and decided not to assault the besieged towns, but they would from time to time advance on Carthage to terrorize the city.<ref>Polybius 1.73.7</ref>\n\nWith their navy shattered in the [[First Punic War]] and their mercenaries in revolt, Carthage could do little but man the walls as an immediate response to the revolt. Carthage raised an army from citizens and mercenaries,<ref>Polybius 1.73.1-2</ref> trained their cavalry, and refitted their navy,<ref>Polybius 1.73</ref> which probably took until the spring of 240&nbsp;BC. [[Hanno the Great]] was put in command of the army, which included 110 elephants,<ref>Polybius 1.74.3-4</ref> but the exact number of troops is unknown. Hanno chose to relieve Utica,<ref name=\"Polybius 1.74\">Polybius 1.74</ref> since rebels had cut off Carthage from the mainland; Hanno and his army were probably ferried to Utica by the Punic fleet,<ref>{{cite book| last = Lancel| first = Serge| title = Hannibal| year = 1998| publisher = Wiley-Blackwell| isbn = 978-0-631-20631-6| url = https://archive.org/details/hannibal00lanc}}</ref> which was also under siege by the rebel army under Spendius. The exact size of the rebel force is not known. Hanno initially defeated the rebels encamped near Utica and captured the rebel camp, but his negligence and the lax discipline of the Carthaginian army enabled the rebels to regroup, launch a surprise attack, capture the Carthaginian camp, and drive the Carthaginian survivors into Utica.<ref name=\"Polybius 1.74\"/> Hanno\u2019s army later left Utica but failed several times to engage the rebels under favorable conditions. Carthage decided to raise a new army and recalled Hamilcar Barca to command. The rebels continued their blockade of Carthage, Utica, and Hippo Acra.\n\n==Hamilcar Barca given a command==\nWhile Hanno the Great was campaigning against the rebels, Carthage had cobbled together another army raised from citizens, rebel deserters, and newly hired mercenaries, numbering 8,000 foot, 2,000 horse and 70 elephants.<ref>Polybius 1.73.1, 1.75.2</ref> Hamilcar Barca was given command of this force, and he spent some time training his soldiers. Carthage made no fresh move against the rebels. Hanno and his army continued watching the two rebel camps at Hippo Acra. The rebel army under Spendius, numbering 15,000, was blockading Utica. Another 10,000 strong rebel army was encamped near the only bridge across the River Bagradas,<ref>Polybius 1.75.5</ref> the exact location is not known.<ref name=\"Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, pp17\">Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, p. 17.</ref> Note that the course of the Bagradas river changed numerous times since the 3<sup>rd</sup> century BC<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Delile |first1=Hugo |last2=Abichou |first2=Abdelhakim |last3=Gadhoum |first3=Ahmed |last4=Goiran |first4=Jean-Philippe |last5=Pleuger |first5=Elisa |last6=Monchambert |first6=Jean-Yves |last7=Wilson |first7=Andrew |last8=Fentress |first8=Elizabeth |last9=Quinn |first9=Josephine |last10=Ben Jerbania |first10=Imed |last11=Ghozzi |first11=Faouzi |title=The Geoarchaeology of Utica, Tunisia: The Paleogeography of the Mejerda Delta and Hypotheses Concerning the Location of the Ancient Harbor |journal=Geoarchaeology |date=July 2015 |volume=30 |issue=4 |pages=291\u2013306 |doi=https://doi.org/10.1002/gea.21514}}</ref>, therefore the battle likely took place south of the current mouth of the river. \n\nOnce his army was properly trained, Hamilcar did not attack the rebels blockading Carthage head on. Instead, he sought to gain the freedom to maneuver and fight the rebels on his own terms. The rebel base at Tunis and rebel dispositions, which probably barricaded the passes on the hills between Djebdl Ammar and Djebel Nahli, cut Carthage off from the mainland.<ref name=\"Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, pp17\"/> Hamilcar had observed that, when the wind blew from a certain direction, a sandbar was uncovered on the river mouth, which made the Bagradas River fordable.\n\nHamilcar marched his army out of Carthage at night along the north shore of the isthmus towards the mouth of the Bagradas River. His movement was not detected by the rebels and at the first opportunity he crossed the Bagradas River along the sandbar. Hamilcar\u2019s army was free to manoeuvre in the African countryside.\n\n===Composition of Forces===\nCarthaginian citizens normally wore armor, greaves, and Greek style helmets, carried a round shield, long spear, and sword, and fought in phalanx formation. Carthaginian citizens and the Libyo-Phoenicians provided disciplined, well-trained cavalry equipped with thrusting spears and round shields. Any mercenaries in Hanno the Great\u2019s army may have resembled the rebels they were facing. Carthage also used elephants, probably African Forest and Indian elephants as shock troops. The elephants were ridden by specially trained riders, some of whom may have come from ancient India or Syria.\n\nThe rebel army had Libyans, Iberians, Gauls, Greeks, and probably Thracians and Scythians present, along with Campanians and Roman deserters.<ref name=\"Polybius 1.67.7\">Polybius 1.67.7</ref> The Libyan heavy infantry fought in close formation, armed with long spears and round shields, wearing helmets and linen cuirasses. The light Libyan infantry carried javelins and a small shield, same as Iberian light infantry. The Iberian infantry wore purple bordered white tunics and leather headgear. The heavy Iberian infantry fought in a dense phalanx, armed with heavy throwing spears, long body shields, and short thrusting swords.<ref>{{cite book| author = Paul Bentley Kern| title = Ancient Siege Warfare| year = 1999| publisher = Indiana University Press| isbn = 978-0-253-33546-3| page = 32 }}</ref> Campanian, Sardinian, Sicel, and Gallic infantry fought in their native gear,<ref>{{cite book| last = Markoe| first = Glenn| title = Phoenicians| year = 2000| publisher = University of California Press| isbn = 978-0-520-22614-2| pages = 84\u201386 }}</ref> but often were equipped by Carthage. Sicels, Sardinians, and other Sicilians were equipped like Greek [[Hoplites]], as were the Sicilian Greek mercenaries. Balearic Slingers fought in their native gear.\n\nNumidians provided superb light cavalry armed with bundles of javelins and riding without bridle or saddle, and light infantry armed with javelins. Iberians and Gauls also provided cavalry, which relied on the all out charge.\n\n==The battle==\nHamilcar\u2019s army completed the river crossing unmolested and undetected by the rebels, and then moved towards the rebel camp near the bridge. Spendius led 15,000 troops from Utica to confront Hamilcar, while 10,000 rebels from the camp near the bridge also advanced towards Hamilcar\u2019s position.<ref name=\"Polybius 1.67.7\"/> Caught in a pincer movement, Hamilcar started to march north. The two rebels forces joined up and began to march north on a parallel course. The army of Spendius outnumbered Hamilcar\u2019s army two to one, so he could afford to form his army in two lines, although the rebels had no elephants and nothing is known of their cavalry. Spendius extended his left flank to the north in an attempt to outflank the Carthaginians. His intention was to have his right flank stop the Carthaginian movement north while his main force attacked and pushed the Carthaginain army towards the river.<ref>Polybius 1.76.1-5</ref>\n\n===Hamilcar\u2019s maneuver===\nSpendius' plan was foiled by Himalcar Barca\u2019s brilliant counter-maneuver, which enabled his outnumbered and seemingly outmaneuvered army to emerge victorious in the ensuing battle. Exactly what Hamilcar did is not clearly known and the issue has been much discussed.<ref name=\"Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, pp17\"/><ref>Hoyos Dexter, The Truceless War, p. 115\u2013124.</ref> It is known that Hamilcar pretended to retreat, which caused the rebels to launch a disorderly attack, while Hamilcar got his soldiers in battle formation to crush the rebels.\n\n====About turn====\n[[Image:Macar1.PNG|150px|right|thumb|Battle of Macar 240 BC. A generic representation, giving one possible scenario, not to exact scale and path of troop movement are inexact because of lack of primary source data]]\n\nAccording to one line of thought,<ref>Bagnall, Nigel, The Punic Wars, p. 116\u2013117.</ref> the Carthaginian army's order of march had the [[War Elephant]]s leading the column, with the light troops and cavalry behind the elephants. Heavy infantry formed the rearguard, and the whole army marched in a single file in battle formation.\n\nWhen Hamilcar observed Spendius extending his battle line to outflank the Carthaginian right flank and cut off the Carthaginian army\u2019s line of advance, he ordered his elephants to turn right, away from the rebel army. The cavalry and light infantry did the same after the elephants, while the heavy infantry continued to move forward. The rebels mistook this for a withdrawal and rushed forward to engage. This wild charge disordered their battle line, some rebel units moving ahead of others.<ref>Polybius 1.76.5</ref>\n\nThe elephants then again turned right, followed by the Carthaginian light infantry and cavalry, so they were now moving south. Parallel to the heavy infantry in the opposite direction The Carthaginian infantry, moving northwards, stopped, turned left and formed a battle line, facing the onrushing rebels. The elephants, light infantry and cavalry are now positioned behind the Carthaginian heavy infantry battle line.\n\nThe Carthaginian elephants, light infantry and cavalry again turned right, divided into two divisions, and took their position on both flanks of the Carthaginian heavy infantry. The rebel formations no longer outflanked the Carthaginian army, and a solid battle line now confronted a disorderly rebel army.\n\n====Triple column====\n[[Image:Macar2.PNG|150px|right|thumb|Battle of Macar 240 BC. A generic representation, giving one possible scenario, not to exact scale and path of troop movement are inexact because of lack of primary source data]]\n\nAccording to another line of thought,<ref>Dodge, T.A, Hannibal, pp 135</ref> Hamilcar\u2019s army marched in three separate columns, The war elephants were placed nearest the rebel army. The cavalry and light infantry was in the middle, while the heavy infantry was posted furthest from the rebel army.\n\nAs the three Carthaginian columns moved north, Spendius extended his left flank to overlap the Carthaginian formation and outflank and cut off the Carthaginians. Hamilcar\u2019s army halted its march seeing this development. The cavalry and light infantry, and the elephants turned right, then moved through gaps in the heavy infantry formation. The rebels mistook this as a Carthaginian withdrawal and rushed forward to attack.\n\nThe Carthaginian heavy infantry next turns right, close gaps and form a battle line to face the rebels. The elephants, cavalry and light infantry split into two divisions, and move into position on the flanks of the Carthaginian heavy infantry. The rebel formations no longer outflanked the Carthaginian army, and a solid battle line confronted a disorderly rebel formation.\n\n===Punic Victory===\nAs the numerically superior but outgeneraled rebels closed and confronted the solid Carthaginian battle line, pandemonium ensued. Instead of hitting the Carthaginians with an orderly formation of infantry en masse, some rebel units engaged the Carthaginians before other units could arrive in support, while others stopped to regroup. As a result, some rebel units were thrown back by the Carthaginians, or as some of the units stopped their charge, the units following them ploughed straight into their back. Battle cohesion was lost and, before the rebels could reorder and regroup, Carthaginian cavalry and infantry charged the entangled rebel units. Scores of rebels were killed, and as the Carthaginian infantry followed up the cavalry and elephant charge, the rebel army broke and scattered, having lost 6,000 of their number. Carthaginian pursuit secured 2,000 prisoners.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nThe surviving rebels fled either to Utica or to their camp beside the bridge. Hamilcar, after mopping up the battle field, advanced on the rebel camp, forcing the rebels to flee to Tunes, where they were reunited with their commander Spendius. Hamilcar then moved towards Utica, forcing the rebels to flee to Hippo Acra. The rebel blockade of Utica was broken. Hamilcar had the choice to join up with Hanno and try to lift the rebel blockade of Hippo Acra as well. Instead he began to mop up the lands beside the Bagradas River, by force or diplomacy asserting Carthaginian authority over the rebel Libyan towns, thus cutting off the rebels from sources funds, recruits and provisions and ensuring Carthage can tap the same resources.\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n=== Bibliography ===\nThe main source for information about ''The Mercenary War'' comes from [[Polybius]], a Greek historian writing many years after the events portrayed here, because no Punic [[primary source]]s survived into modern times. It is likely that he based much of his account on now-lost works of prior Greek and Roman historians, who are unlikely to have had an less biased view of Carthage.\n\n* [[Polybius]], [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#70 ''The Histories''].\n* [[Appian]], ''History of Rome: The Sicilian Wars''.\n* {{cite book| last = Bagnall| first = Nigel| title = The Punic Wars| year = 1990| publisher = Macmillan| isbn = 0-312-34214-4| url = https://archive.org/details/punicwars00bagn}}\n* {{cite book| author = Goldsworthy, Adrian| title = The Fall of Carthage| year = 2003| publisher = Cassel Military Paperbacks| isbn = 0-304-36642-0 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Miles| first = Richard| title = Carthage Must Be Destroyed| year = 2011| publisher = Penguin Group| isbn = 978-0-141-01809-6 }}\n* {{cite book| author = Lazanby, Johm Francis| title = The First Punic War| year = 2003| publisher = Routledge| isbn = 1-85728-136-5 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Lancel| first = Serge| title = Hannibal| year = 1999| publisher = Blackwell Publishers Limited| isbn = 0-631-21848-3 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Dodge| first = Theodore A.| title = Hannibal| url = https://archive.org/details/hannibalhistoryo00dodg| url-access = registration| origyear = 1885| year = 2004| publisher = Da Capo Press| isbn = 978-0-306-81362-7 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Bath| first = Tony| title = Hannibal\u2019s Campaigns| year = 1999| publisher = Barns & Noble Books| isbn = 0-88029-817-0| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780880298179}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Punic Wars navbox}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tunisia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle of the Bagradas River, -240}}\n\n[[Category:240 BC]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Mercenary War|Bagradas River, -240]]\n[[Category:240s BC conflicts|Bagradas River, -240]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Battle during the First Punic War}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict    = Battle of the Bagradas River\n|partof      = Carthage's [[Mercenary War]]\n| image      = Macar240.PNG\n| image_size = 300\n|caption     =\n|date        = Autumn 240 BC\n|place       = [[Medjerda River]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type    =\n|map_relief  =\n|latitude    =\n|longitude   =\n|map_size    =\n|map_marksize =\n|map_caption =\n|map_label   =\n|territory   =\n|result      = Carthaginian victory\n|status      =\n|combatants_header =\n|combatant1  = [[Ancient Carthage|Carthage]]\n|combatant2  = Rebel mercenaries<br>Rebelling Libyan towns and cities\n|commander1  = [[Hamilcar Barca]]<ref>Polybius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#73 1:73.1].</ref>\n|commander2  = Spendius\n|units1      =\n|units2      =\n|strength1   = <br>8,000 infantry, 2,000 cavalry, 70 elephants<ref>Polybius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#75 1:75.1-75.2].</ref>\n|strength2   = Unclear, an estimated 25,000. 15,000 under Spendius at [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]], 10,000 near the bridge on Bagradas River.<ref>Polybius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#73 1:76.1]</ref>\n|casualties1 = Unknown\n|casualties2 = 6,000 killed<br>2,000 captured\n|casualties3 =\n|notes       =\n|campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Mercenary War}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of the Bagradas River''' or '''the Macar''' ({{c.|240}}{{nbsp}}BC) was fought between [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] forces and part of the combined forces of Carthage's former [[mercenary]] armies during the [[Mercenary War]] which it used to conduct the [[First Punic War]] and those of rebelling Libyan cities. After the forces of [[Hanno the Great]] were defeated at [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]], and failed to engage the mercenaries afterwards despite favorable conditions, Carthage raised a new army under [[Hamilcar Barca]] in Carthage. Hamilcar managed to leave Carthage despite the rebel blockade of the city and cross the Bagradas River (the ancient name of the [[Medjerda River|Medjerda]]). Rebel armies from besieging Utica and the camp guarded the bridge on the Bagradas River. Hamilcar Barca, by brilliant maneuvering, defeated the combined rebel army. This was the first major Carthaginian victory of the war. A description of the battle forms one of the grandiose set-piece scenes of [[Gustave Flaubert]]'s novel, Salammbo.\n\n== Background ==\n{{further|Mercenary War}}\nThe [[First Punic War]] ended with the Roman victory in the [[Battle of Aegates Islands|Battle of the Aegates Islands]] in March 241 BC and Carthage authorizing [[Hamilcar Barca]] to start peace negotiations with Rome. The eventual settlement between [[Roman republic|Rome]] and Carthage included evacuation of Sicily by Carthage and payment of 3,200 silver talents to Rome as war reparations: 1,000 (21 tons of silver) immediately and 2,200 (56 ton of silver) in ten yearly installments. After paying Rome the indemnity which was part of the treaty,<ref>Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#62 1:62.8-63.3].</ref> it could not easily pay the army of some 20,000 [[mercenaries]] it had employed to fight against Rome.<ref name=\"PAY\">Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#66 66.5], and [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#68 1:68.12]</ref>\n\nDelays in dealing with the mercenaries eventually led to the gathering of the entire army and their families in Sicca Veneria (modern [[El Kef]]), where they demanded payment from the Carthaginian negotiator [[Hanno the Great]].<ref>Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#66 1:66.6-66.12].</ref> The exact amount owned the mercenaries can only be guessed, but given the back pay, ration money and any other rewards promised, it probably was a substantial amount,<ref name=\"Hoyos Dexter pp27-31\">Hoyos Dexter, The Truceless War, p. 27\u201331</ref> which the mercenaries inflated after they reached Sicca. When Hanno refused their demands, as Carthage actually hoped to reduce the payment amount, and mercenaries were unsympathetic about the financial difficulties of Carthage, the negotiations broke down and the mercenaries seized [[Tunis]].<ref>Po0lybius 1.66.1-1.6712</ref> Carthage then sent provisions to Tunis and agreed to all the demands of the mercenaries, and sent Gisco to pay off the demanded amount.<ref>Appian, [https://www.livius.org/ap-ark/appian/appian_sicily.html#%A74 2.7]; Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#67 1:67.1-68.13].</ref>\n\nGisco began to pay off the mercenaries nationality by nationality,<ref>Polybius 1.68.1, 1.69.3</ref> and events might have ended there, but two mercenary leaders, Spendius and Mathos, fomented revolt among the Libyan troops, for their own personal reasons, and were eventually able to persuade the entire mercenary army to revolt. The mercenaries seized the Carthaginian negotiators and the money. Matho used the funds to pay off the amount due to the mercenaries and fund the war effort.<ref>Polybius 1.69.4, 1.70.6</ref> After settling the mercenary payments, the rebels called upon the Libyan towns and cities under Carthaginian control to join the revolt. Several Libyan cities joined the revolt, providing men and funds (Libyan women donated personal possessions and jewels)<ref>Polybius 1.72.5-6</ref> to gather a force of 70,000.<ref>Polybius 1.70.8-9</ref> These events probably took place in the autumn-winter of 241 BC.\n\n==Opening moves==\nMatho divided the rebel army into several detachments. Matho took two armies to cut off the cities of [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]] and Hippacritae, while an army took up position along the only bridge over the River Macar linking Carthage and Utica. Spendius cut off Carthage from the mainland<ref>Polybius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#68 1:68.4-68.13].</ref> while rebels made Tunis their main base. The rebels had no siege weapons and decided not to assault the besieged towns, but they would from time to time advance on Carthage to terrorize the city.<ref>Polybius 1.73.7</ref>\n\nWith their navy shattered in the [[First Punic War]] and their mercenaries in revolt, Carthage could do little but man the walls as an immediate response to the revolt. Carthage raised an army from citizens and mercenaries,<ref>Polybius 1.73.1-2</ref> trained their cavalry, and refitted their navy,<ref>Polybius 1.73</ref> which probably took until the spring of 240&nbsp;BC. [[Hanno the Great]] was put in command of the army, which included 110 elephants,<ref>Polybius 1.74.3-4</ref> but the exact number of troops is unknown. Hanno chose to relieve Utica,<ref name=\"Polybius 1.74\">Polybius 1.74</ref> since rebels had cut off Carthage from the mainland; Hanno and his army were probably ferried to Utica by the Punic fleet,<ref>{{cite book| last = Lancel| first = Serge| title = Hannibal| year = 1998| publisher = Wiley-Blackwell| isbn = 978-0-631-20631-6| url = https://archive.org/details/hannibal00lanc}}</ref> which was also under siege by the rebel army under Spendius. The exact size of the rebel force is not known. Hanno initially defeated the rebels encamped near Utica and captured the rebel camp, but his negligence and the lax discipline of the Carthaginian army enabled the rebels to regroup, launch a surprise attack, capture the Carthaginian camp, and drive the Carthaginian survivors into Utica.<ref name=\"Polybius 1.74\"/> Hanno\u2019s army later left Utica but failed several times to engage the rebels under favorable conditions. Carthage decided to raise a new army and recalled Hamilcar Barca to command. The rebels continued their blockade of Carthage, Utica, and Hippo Acra.\n\n==Hamilcar Barca given a command==\nWhile Hanno the Great was campaigning against the rebels, Carthage had cobbled together another army raised from citizens, rebel deserters, and newly hired mercenaries, numbering 8,000 foot, 2,000 horse and 70 elephants.<ref>Polybius 1.73.1, 1.75.2</ref> Hamilcar Barca was given command of this force, and he spent some time training his soldiers. Carthage made no fresh move against the rebels. Hanno and his army continued watching the two rebel camps at Hippo Acra. The rebel army under Spendius, numbering 15,000, was blockading Utica. Another 10,000 strong rebel army was encamped near the only bridge across the River Bagradas,<ref>Polybius 1.75.5</ref> the exact location is not known.<ref name=\"Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, pp17\">Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, p. 17.</ref> Note that the course of the Bagradas river changed numerous times since the 3<sup>rd</sup> century BC,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Delile |first1=Hugo |last2=Abichou |first2=Abdelhakim |last3=Gadhoum |first3=Ahmed |last4=Goiran |first4=Jean-Philippe |last5=Pleuger |first5=Elisa |last6=Monchambert |first6=Jean-Yves |last7=Wilson |first7=Andrew |last8=Fentress |first8=Elizabeth |last9=Quinn |first9=Josephine |last10=Ben Jerbania |first10=Imed |last11=Ghozzi |first11=Faouzi |title=The Geoarchaeology of Utica, Tunisia: The Paleogeography of the Mejerda Delta and Hypotheses Concerning the Location of the Ancient Harbor |journal=Geoarchaeology |date=July 2015 |volume=30 |issue=4 |pages=291\u2013306 |doi=https://doi.org/10.1002/gea.21514}}</ref>, therefore the battle likely took place south of the current mouth of the river. \n\nOnce his army was properly trained, Hamilcar did not attack the rebels blockading Carthage head on. Instead, he sought to gain the freedom to maneuver and fight the rebels on his own terms. The rebel base at Tunis and rebel dispositions, which probably barricaded the passes on the hills between Djebdl Ammar and Djebel Nahli, cut Carthage off from the mainland.<ref name=\"Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, pp17\"/> Hamilcar had observed that, when the wind blew from a certain direction, a sandbar was uncovered on the river mouth, which made the Bagradas River fordable.\n\nHamilcar marched his army out of Carthage at night along the north shore of the isthmus towards the mouth of the Bagradas River. His movement was not detected by the rebels and at the first opportunity he crossed the Bagradas River along the sandbar. Hamilcar\u2019s army was free to manoeuvre in the African countryside.\n\n===Composition of Forces===\nCarthaginian citizens normally wore armor, greaves, and Greek style helmets, carried a round shield, long spear, and sword, and fought in phalanx formation. Carthaginian citizens and the Libyo-Phoenicians provided disciplined, well-trained cavalry equipped with thrusting spears and round shields. Any mercenaries in Hanno the Great\u2019s army may have resembled the rebels they were facing. Carthage also used elephants, probably African Forest and Indian elephants as shock troops. The elephants were ridden by specially trained riders, some of whom may have come from ancient India or Syria.\n\nThe rebel army had Libyans, Iberians, Gauls, Greeks, and probably Thracians and Scythians present, along with Campanians and Roman deserters.<ref name=\"Polybius 1.67.7\">Polybius 1.67.7</ref> The Libyan heavy infantry fought in close formation, armed with long spears and round shields, wearing helmets and linen cuirasses. The light Libyan infantry carried javelins and a small shield, same as Iberian light infantry. The Iberian infantry wore purple bordered white tunics and leather headgear. The heavy Iberian infantry fought in a dense phalanx, armed with heavy throwing spears, long body shields, and short thrusting swords.<ref>{{cite book| author = Paul Bentley Kern| title = Ancient Siege Warfare| year = 1999| publisher = Indiana University Press| isbn = 978-0-253-33546-3| page = 32 }}</ref> Campanian, Sardinian, Sicel, and Gallic infantry fought in their native gear,<ref>{{cite book| last = Markoe| first = Glenn| title = Phoenicians| year = 2000| publisher = University of California Press| isbn = 978-0-520-22614-2| pages = 84\u201386 }}</ref> but often were equipped by Carthage. Sicels, Sardinians, and other Sicilians were equipped like Greek [[Hoplites]], as were the Sicilian Greek mercenaries. Balearic Slingers fought in their native gear.\n\nNumidians provided superb light cavalry armed with bundles of javelins and riding without bridle or saddle, and light infantry armed with javelins. Iberians and Gauls also provided cavalry, which relied on the all out charge.\n\n==The battle==\nHamilcar\u2019s army completed the river crossing unmolested and undetected by the rebels, and then moved towards the rebel camp near the bridge. Spendius led 15,000 troops from Utica to confront Hamilcar, while 10,000 rebels from the camp near the bridge also advanced towards Hamilcar\u2019s position.<ref name=\"Polybius 1.67.7\"/> Caught in a pincer movement, Hamilcar started to march north. The two rebels forces joined up and began to march north on a parallel course. The army of Spendius outnumbered Hamilcar\u2019s army two to one, so he could afford to form his army in two lines, although the rebels had no elephants and nothing is known of their cavalry. Spendius extended his left flank to the north in an attempt to outflank the Carthaginians. His intention was to have his right flank stop the Carthaginian movement north while his main force attacked and pushed the Carthaginain army towards the river.<ref>Polybius 1.76.1-5</ref>\n\n===Hamilcar\u2019s maneuver===\nSpendius' plan was foiled by Himalcar Barca\u2019s brilliant counter-maneuver, which enabled his outnumbered and seemingly outmaneuvered army to emerge victorious in the ensuing battle. Exactly what Hamilcar did is not clearly known and the issue has been much discussed.<ref name=\"Lancel, Serge, Hannibal, pp17\"/><ref>Hoyos Dexter, The Truceless War, p. 115\u2013124.</ref> It is known that Hamilcar pretended to retreat, which caused the rebels to launch a disorderly attack, while Hamilcar got his soldiers in battle formation to crush the rebels.\n\n====About turn====\n[[Image:Macar1.PNG|150px|right|thumb|Battle of Macar 240 BC. A generic representation, giving one possible scenario, not to exact scale and path of troop movement are inexact because of lack of primary source data]]\n\nAccording to one line of thought,<ref>Bagnall, Nigel, The Punic Wars, p. 116\u2013117.</ref> the Carthaginian army's order of march had the [[War Elephant]]s leading the column, with the light troops and cavalry behind the elephants. Heavy infantry formed the rearguard, and the whole army marched in a single file in battle formation.\n\nWhen Hamilcar observed Spendius extending his battle line to outflank the Carthaginian right flank and cut off the Carthaginian army\u2019s line of advance, he ordered his elephants to turn right, away from the rebel army. The cavalry and light infantry did the same after the elephants, while the heavy infantry continued to move forward. The rebels mistook this for a withdrawal and rushed forward to engage. This wild charge disordered their battle line, some rebel units moving ahead of others.<ref>Polybius 1.76.5</ref>\n\nThe elephants then again turned right, followed by the Carthaginian light infantry and cavalry, so they were now moving south. Parallel to the heavy infantry in the opposite direction The Carthaginian infantry, moving northwards, stopped, turned left and formed a battle line, facing the onrushing rebels. The elephants, light infantry and cavalry are now positioned behind the Carthaginian heavy infantry battle line.\n\nThe Carthaginian elephants, light infantry and cavalry again turned right, divided into two divisions, and took their position on both flanks of the Carthaginian heavy infantry. The rebel formations no longer outflanked the Carthaginian army, and a solid battle line now confronted a disorderly rebel army.\n\n====Triple column====\n[[Image:Macar2.PNG|150px|right|thumb|Battle of Macar 240 BC. A generic representation, giving one possible scenario, not to exact scale and path of troop movement are inexact because of lack of primary source data]]\n\nAccording to another line of thought,<ref>Dodge, T.A, Hannibal, pp 135</ref> Hamilcar\u2019s army marched in three separate columns, The war elephants were placed nearest the rebel army. The cavalry and light infantry was in the middle, while the heavy infantry was posted furthest from the rebel army.\n\nAs the three Carthaginian columns moved north, Spendius extended his left flank to overlap the Carthaginian formation and outflank and cut off the Carthaginians. Hamilcar\u2019s army halted its march seeing this development. The cavalry and light infantry, and the elephants turned right, then moved through gaps in the heavy infantry formation. The rebels mistook this as a Carthaginian withdrawal and rushed forward to attack.\n\nThe Carthaginian heavy infantry next turns right, close gaps and form a battle line to face the rebels. The elephants, cavalry and light infantry split into two divisions, and move into position on the flanks of the Carthaginian heavy infantry. The rebel formations no longer outflanked the Carthaginian army, and a solid battle line confronted a disorderly rebel formation.\n\n===Punic Victory===\nAs the numerically superior but outgeneraled rebels closed and confronted the solid Carthaginian battle line, pandemonium ensued. Instead of hitting the Carthaginians with an orderly formation of infantry en masse, some rebel units engaged the Carthaginians before other units could arrive in support, while others stopped to regroup. As a result, some rebel units were thrown back by the Carthaginians, or as some of the units stopped their charge, the units following them ploughed straight into their back. Battle cohesion was lost and, before the rebels could reorder and regroup, Carthaginian cavalry and infantry charged the entangled rebel units. Scores of rebels were killed, and as the Carthaginian infantry followed up the cavalry and elephant charge, the rebel army broke and scattered, having lost 6,000 of their number. Carthaginian pursuit secured 2,000 prisoners.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nThe surviving rebels fled either to Utica or to their camp beside the bridge. Hamilcar, after mopping up the battle field, advanced on the rebel camp, forcing the rebels to flee to Tunes, where they were reunited with their commander Spendius. Hamilcar then moved towards Utica, forcing the rebels to flee to Hippo Acra. The rebel blockade of Utica was broken. Hamilcar had the choice to join up with Hanno and try to lift the rebel blockade of Hippo Acra as well. Instead he began to mop up the lands beside the Bagradas River, by force or diplomacy asserting Carthaginian authority over the rebel Libyan towns, thus cutting off the rebels from sources funds, recruits and provisions and ensuring Carthage can tap the same resources.\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n=== Bibliography ===\nThe main source for information about ''The Mercenary War'' comes from [[Polybius]], a Greek historian writing many years after the events portrayed here, because no Punic [[primary source]]s survived into modern times. It is likely that he based much of his account on now-lost works of prior Greek and Roman historians, who are unlikely to have had an less biased view of Carthage.\n\n* [[Polybius]], [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html#70 ''The Histories''].\n* [[Appian]], ''History of Rome: The Sicilian Wars''.\n* {{cite book| last = Bagnall| first = Nigel| title = The Punic Wars| year = 1990| publisher = Macmillan| isbn = 0-312-34214-4| url = https://archive.org/details/punicwars00bagn}}\n* {{cite book| author = Goldsworthy, Adrian| title = The Fall of Carthage| year = 2003| publisher = Cassel Military Paperbacks| isbn = 0-304-36642-0 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Miles| first = Richard| title = Carthage Must Be Destroyed| year = 2011| publisher = Penguin Group| isbn = 978-0-141-01809-6 }}\n* {{cite book| author = Lazanby, Johm Francis| title = The First Punic War| year = 2003| publisher = Routledge| isbn = 1-85728-136-5 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Lancel| first = Serge| title = Hannibal| year = 1999| publisher = Blackwell Publishers Limited| isbn = 0-631-21848-3 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Dodge| first = Theodore A.| title = Hannibal| url = https://archive.org/details/hannibalhistoryo00dodg| url-access = registration| origyear = 1885| year = 2004| publisher = Da Capo Press| isbn = 978-0-306-81362-7 }}\n* {{cite book| last = Bath| first = Tony| title = Hannibal\u2019s Campaigns| year = 1999| publisher = Barns & Noble Books| isbn = 0-88029-817-0| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780880298179}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Punic Wars navbox}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tunisia}}\n\n{{DEFAU